The franchise sale of his hotel helped Lukas Pytloun to win the Best Individual Entrepreneur competition.
The winner of last year’s Best Individual Entrepreneur competition was Lukas Pytloun, a 28-year-old entrepreneur.
His adventure to success is like in a movie.
Lukas Pytloun loved to travel.
And abroad, he realized that in Liberec there was a lack of quality hosting site at a reasonable price.
From his savings on what he had earned while working abroad and with the help of a bank loan he bought a small building of 5 apartments half demolished.
Knowing that he was still a third-year graduate student, it was a courageous action.
“The ratio of quality to price of accommodation in our region made me want to do something,” says Lucas Pytloun.
He began renting the first rebuilt apartment to foreign workers.
He reinvested the profit in the building which he transformed into a pension with 54 beds.
Since then, his entrepreneurial activity has allowed him to open in Liberec 4 guesthouses, two style restaurants and two hotels with a total capacity of almost 300 beds of all categories of accommodation.
The most comfortable of them was until recently the four-star Pytloun design hotel.
This year, he had another one of the same quality.
“We just signed a contract with a hotel in Ostrova U Tise where we sold our franchise concept and other candidates for the Pytloun hotel franchise showed up.”
"And for the sale of the license for the commissioning of a large-scale hotel the victory in the Entrepreneur of the Year competition served well," adds Pytloun with appreciation.
The victory brought him more popularity and to be known in Liberec and its surroundings.
“People recognized me on the streets, congratulated me often and, I must say, it was very nice,” he recalls.
He recommends participation in this competition to all those who strive to do something.
It is not necessary to win but any opportunity to be visible is good.
He says he is still using his contacts and knowledge that he could not have obtained in any other way.
"With those I met through the contest I started to maintain business relationships regularly.
According to him, the reputation related to success has also had an impact on employees.
And he's about 70.
“I observe in their homes above all the loyalty and pride of having engaged in something that has been generally recognized.”
"This is by far not the only result of my personal work, but the result of a good work of all of us together.
“Only my name is pushed forward,” says Lucas Pytloun modestly.
I wish my successor a better year than the one we had at Farmet.
The euphoria of victory was quickly replaced by the effects of the crisis.
Thanks to the sense of purpose of the winner Farmet has the worst moments behind it.
The one who came to fetch the award from Slovansky dum for the first place in the contest for the Firm of the Year organized by Vodaphone last year is Karel Zdarsky the owner of the Farmet company.
The jury rewarded the efforts with which it transformed a tool shop in Ceska Skalice into a firm with a turnover of 100 million crowns.
“I can say that the award has not only encouraged me and my employees but also increased our self-confidence to fight the competition,” said the winner of last year’s competition.
At the beginning of the history of the Farmet company there was a desire to do something useful.
And so when the state offered to the father of Karel Zdrasky to rent the small workshop as compensation after the confiscation of property by the communists, he did not hesitate long, refused a career in a firm where he worked at the time, and created a company with a few comrades in his father's entourage for the manufacture of plastic bathtubs.
Not long after they began to specialize in presses for vegetable oil.
After eighteen years it has become the largest manufacturer of automatic presses in Central Europe.
The company was known even in the non-specialized public after the success obtained in the contest through the media.
“Not only did our customers start to really get to know the Farmet brand better but also foreign partners who started to realize that they were collaborating with a company that had the greatest success in its home country,” says Karel Zdarsky.
But the past year has not happened at Farmet only in the euphoria of victory.
The company's assessment was based on the 2008 and part of 2009 economic results.
And in 2009 it was the most difficult year for the sale of engineering machinery.
At the height of the crisis, which did not really affect citizens, companies were forced to stop their investment projects and begin to limit their purchases of new materials and technologies.
“Obviously we did not escape this situation.”
“Revenues fell by 40 percent, and we had to limit our production and even lay off,” says Karel Zdarsky.
A viable society must know that from time to time unpopular measures must be taken.
