Households will pay an additional one hundred crowns a month for housing.
Starting in January, households will have to pay a supplement not only for all types of energy but also for water and sanitation, heating supplies and in some places rents will also increase.
Families will therefore have to draw up to a hundred crowns monthly from their wallets from January onwards than now.
Electricity increases by 4.6 percent, gas by almost 2 percent more expensive, in some localities you will have to pay up to a tenth more for water supply and in many places central heating supplies will also be more expensive.
The increase in electricity is expected to be close to 100 kroner per year for households in flats than currently.
However, all suppliers have lowered electricity prices given the significant development in encouraging the production of renewable energies, particularly photovoltaic batteries.
The gas increases moderately but of course at the time when people need it most to heat and therefore have the highest consumption.
One can also count a hundred crowns more.
Although electricity and gas are increasing throughout the Czech Republic, the change in the price of central heating differs from city to city.
It is mainly the largest municipalities that plan the price increase.
For example, households in Pardubice or Hradec Kraloce will pay from January for central heating almost 50 crowns more per month, families in Liberec will pay more than 1000 crowns annually.
For the residents of Prague is preparing a 9 percent increase for water and sanitation in case the city increases infrastructure rents.
If the rents do not change, the people of Prague will pay an additional 6.8 percent.
The price in Prague will still be among the lowest in comparison with the whole country.
In North Bohemia, where prices are already among the highest, water and sanitation are up 7.4 percent.
For example, rent prices will increase significantly in the 450 thousand apartments for rent from January onwards, i.e. at the end of the regulation.
For example, the company CPI Byty, which owns almost 2,500 apartments in Usti nad Labem, has decided to increase by up to 100 percent.
Those who disagree with the new rent increase will be brought before the courts by the company.
The regulated rents people pay in nearly 300,000 apartments could increase by 10 percent next year.
Czech children get drunk on rum and fernet. Beer is no longer fashionable and acts very slowly.
Fernet, rum, vodka and exceptionally also the best brand of whisky are stolen from parents.
These are drinks that most often bring those who get drunk, who are not yet fifteen years old, into the hands of the doctor.
Children who are treated in the hospital for recidivism are no exception.
This results from the experience of doctors who encounter cases similar to admissions from children's departments of hospitals.
"Beers or wines are no longer fashionable because it takes time to get drunk."
“The trend is really strong alcohol,” says Ludek Pelikan, head of the children’s department at the Horovice hospital in central Bohemia.
"When they manage to chip a bottle of popsicle in the closet, it's sometimes about whisky but it's the fernet and vodka that prevail."
“Vodka has this advantage that they can mix it with fruit juice and thus not smell it,” says the head of the department.
Eva Jurinova, spokesperson for the Motol hospital, also gives him reason.
"In general, it's rum or fernet."
"It's the alcohol in fashion today, especially in elementary schools."
"In some cases it was slivovice that they brought back from the house," Jurinova added.
According to Department Chief Pelikan, seeing drunken children between the ages of thirteen and fourteen at hospital admissions is a normal phenomenon.
Before working in Horovice since last year, he was in Motol where he practiced ten years precisely in pediatrics where ambulances brought schoolchildren from the wide surroundings completely drunk.
A young woman was hospitalized four times.
"She started her career at the age of twelve when she was brought with 3.5 per thousand alcohol in the blood with an additional mixture with ecstasy," the doctor described this particularly important case.
"She was at the Holesovice Exhibition Park at a party."
"What's interesting is that it didn't seem strange to the mother that her daughter was absent for 48 hours," said the Director of the Department astonished.
It is precisely the parents' disinterestedness or their unusual tolerance for their offspring to drink that are the main cause of the development of alcoholism in children.
According to specialists, however, there is no talk of dependence, in its strict sense, for children.
"Under the term alcoholic we hear a chronic dependence on alcohol for several years with all the phenomena that result but that are not found in children."
“For those who use alcohol over and over again, it’s rather a significantly unfavorable socio-familial background,” said Department Chief Pelikan.
According to spokeswoman Jurinova, about forty drunk children were hospitalized this year until mid-November at the pediatric clinic in Motol.
Only cases with severe intoxication requiring hospitalization are included in the statistic.
Drunken children who are after emergency care brought home by parents or police are not counted.
In addition to the cases of children who sit down and drink a bottle of alcohol after school, according to Pelikan there are three seasonal waves with which one can count: Witch's Day, New Year's Eve and the end of the school year.
"Either they drink out of spite after bad results or on the contrary they celebrate the beginning of the holidays."
"Of course I experienced at Witch's Day an admission of 7 drunken children at once," Pelikan said.
The drunken child who spent the night in the hospital in detoxification under medical control is paradoxically in a better position than the one who returned home and suffers the next day from the "hangover".
Morning headaches caused by dehydration and a lack of glucose are eliminated by an infusion of glucose and nutrients that the body needs.
“They are better off because they have a great evening and then a sweet wake-up call and nothing hurts them.”
“They’re just amazed at where they are,” Pelikan adds, knowing that from time to time it spoils the patients’ good mood at least with the bill to pay for their care.
Ambulance transportation and hospitalization on intensive care beds can go up to tens of thousands of crowns.
“Once in a while, I applied this as a means of education by counting these children how much their drunkenness has cost and that they could spend the entire summer in seasonal work to repay a single evening,” Pelikan added.
However, according to him, the health insurance companies in their regression management, which should recover from the parents the burdens related to care, do not deal with cases of drunk children.
Two L-159 planes are in foreign hands for the first time in Spain.
Two of the five L-159 planes, for which the Ministry of Defense traded Casa C-295M transport planes, took off Tuesday for Seville, Spain, where the aircraft manufacturer Casa-EADS is based.
This is the first time that aircraft of this type have become the property of someone other than the Czech army.
However, they have been abroad as part of exercises or demonstration flights.
These are the two-seater versions of the L-159T1 that were previously in service in the Czech Army and were in flight condition.
The remaining three aircraft are single-seat versions of the L-159.
These are currently parked at Aero Vodochody and the commercial intermediary - the firm Omnipol - took them into account last week.
According to Jan Pejsek of the press department of the Ministry of Defense, the physical departure of the Vodochody planes is currently unknown.
“The L-159 single-seat aircraft planned for the exchange were taken on long-stored aircraft without causing additional charges or investments for the Ministry of Defence.”
"The L-159 T1 two-seaters have been traded in the state," he told Pravo Pejsek.
The ministry signed an agreement with Aero Vodochody in May 2009 for the conversion of four unused L-159 single-seaters into two two-seaters worth 200 million crowns.
The army took delivery of the first aircraft in July, with the second scheduled for delivery later this year.
According to Pejsek EADS is committed to introducing the aircraft into the equipment of some Alliance countries.
“In the contract it is clearly stated that the one who takes the L-159 aircraft into account is EADS and that they will be used to train pilots from NATO member countries.”
"It is therefore the business of the one who is considering how to achieve this," Pejsek said.
Hospodarske noviny announced some time ago that the Spanish army is not interested in the L-159.
The exchange of five L-159s for a Casa plane and the purchase of three other planes for 3.5 billion crowns was approved last year by the government of Mirek Topomanek.
The Ministry of Defence did not launch a tender and contacted EADS directly.
The defence department argued that the exchange ensured a future export of the L-159 abroad.
The Czech army bought 72 aircraft from Aero Vodochody and only uses 24, wanting to sell the rest.
The purchase of Casa aircraft will likely have legal implications.
However, the European Commission has filed a complaint against the Czech Ministry of Defence with the European Court of Justice because the aircraft should have been chosen in the context of a European-wide tender and in no case by contacting a manufacturer directly.
The army has already taken delivery of three Casa planes, the last one is expected to arrive at Prague Kbely airport in two weeks.
A longer index than the ring finger is a sign of low cancer risk
Men who have a longer index than the ring finger are at a lower risk of prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published Wednesday by the British magazine Cancer.
This may depend on the level of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our findings show that the relative length of the finger serves as a simple prostate cancer risk test, especially for men before the age of 60," said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help determine which men should be tested for prostate cancer, including by combining with genetic risk or other aggravating factors such as family health history, Eeles added.
During the period 1994-2009 she followed with her colleagues in Britain more than 1500 patients with prostate cancer and at the same time nearly three thousand healthy men.
More than half of the study participants had the index finger of the right hand shorter than the ring finger.
For them as for the 19 percent of those who had fingers of the same length, we found the same probability of prostate cancer.
In the case of those who had the index longer than the ring finger the risk however fell to 33 percent, for men before 60 the decrease in risk reached 87 percent.
The ratio of the length of the two fingers mentioned - formed during the prenatal period - indicates in particular different levels of sex hormones to which the child is exposed in the uterus.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer index.
Previous research had shown that it is precisely testosterone that helps in the development of prostate cancer.
Prof. Vacla Paces, a renowned Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, told CTK that he is aware of the study but does not believe that the relationship between finger length and cancer is "completely demonstrated".
