Americans have a new “smart weapon”
The U.S. military has sent a new “smart” weapon to Afghanistan, known only as the XM-25 code.
The generals believe that this new automatic rifle will have an influence on the conflict there with the Taliban and will “change the game” to their advantage.
The new weapon is like a super-precise gun
Its projectiles are guided by laser with an accuracy of a few meters.
The special 25 mm calibre ammunition developed for this rifle and containing a highly-breaking explosive, actually works like small grenades.
The munitions can be programmed in such a way that they will explode in contact with the target but also at any point in their ballistic trajectory.
It can therefore be used against an enemy that hides behind an obstacle, a wall or a ditch.
It is also not protected from above and when a deadly rain of steel chips falls on it, it can put it out of combat as well.
According to Richard Audette who took part in the development of the XM-25, the new rifle is the first infantry weapon that uses “smart” technology.
"The soldier essentially uses it in such a way that he finds the target, sends him a laser beam that determines the distance, thus obtaining a precise point of view, according to which he corrects his sight site and presses the detent.
"Let's say you aimed at 543 meters."
"When you press the trigger, the weapon loads and fires at a distance of 543 meters plus or minus 1, 2, 3 meters," Audette said.
400 jobs relocated
The Fujitsu Group relocates its subsidiary from Bad Homburg to Frankfurt.
Next year in July, 400 employees will move their current workplace to Astro Park at the Mareinbader Square office building in the Bad Homburg area.
The Japanese group Fujitsu relocates its branch from Bad Homburg to Frankfurt.
As stated Wednesday by the computer manufacturing and maintenance giant, next year in July, the workplace of 400 men and women, located so far on Marienbader Square in the city of Bad Homburg, will be transferred to Astro Park, a huge office complex located on Lyoner Straße in Frankfurt’s Niederrad district.
A spokeswoman for Fujitsu said that in the medium term, the group is expected to bring together another 100 jobs still scattered so far in the region.
The rental offer has been extremely attractive, and the Astro Park open-plan offices are better suited to the way employees work.
In Bad Homburg too, Fujitsu was just a tenant.
Managing Director Bernd Wagner said: “Frankfurt-Niederrad is a prime location with a remarkable infrastructure for us.”
He says that the connection to the airport is precisely of great importance for a global company like Fujitsu.
The relocation of a major company within the region yesterday aroused the joy of the winners and caused the disappointment of the losers.
The head of economic affairs of the municipality of Frankfurt, Markus Frank (CDU), said that once again, a "planetary actor" had been conquered.
It is an "extraordinary profession of faith relative to the place of implantation".
Fujitsu is suitable for the city and its location is an important impetus for Niederrad.
Bad Homburg Mayor Michael Korwisi (Greens) regrets Fujitsu’s decision.
Management very early informed the municipality of this intention.
"It goes without saying that we have offered our help to this company," Korwisi said.
However, friendly relations could not have changed the computer manufacturer's difficulties with the owner of the Marienbader Square building.
In the end, the economic reasons would have been decisive.
It is now a question of preventing such an exceptional place from remaining unoccupied for a long time.
"I hope that the owner and lessor of the building will be cooperative."
Ten years ago, the Town Hall Square building, used so far by Fujitsu and the nearby "small vertical", as well as the rest of the Marienbad Square buildings, were part of the controversial construction project for the spa.
The result of a joint project of the municipality and a private project developer, a new entrance to the city was created between the train station and the City Hall, which drew much criticism, not only because of the impressive layout of the surfaces that used to be used in part as parking, but also because of the height of the buildings.
In 2001, the rating and investment advisory firm, Feri, the computer manufacturer for travel distribution systems, Start Amadeus, as well as Fujitsu, a computer manufacturer at the time still associated with Siemens, moved into the buildings.
In 2006, the German Frankfurt-based Immobilien-Chancen group bought the buildings occupied by Fujitsu along with the Morgan Stanley real estate fund. A year later, these buildings were resold to the Spanish company Falcon Real Estate Investments SA based in Madrid.
The Fujitsu Group, headquartered in Tokyo, is considered the third largest supplier of IT products in the world.
For example, it makes computers and servers available to businesses and also provides essential service.
Its branch located in the Rhine-Main region is one of the largest in Germany: Fujitsu has certainly far more employees in Munich.
The branch, Fujitsu Technology Solutions, leaves Bad Homburg to move to Frankfurt-Niederrad. The other subsidiaries on this site are Fujitsu Services and a company named TDS.
For this, 7000 square meters have taken for rent in the Astro Park building.
This twenty-year-old complex, whose name is reminiscent of its star-shaped plan, is home, among other things, to the headquarters of the Confederation of the electronic and electrotechnical industry.
Amazon eviction - Threats against Mr. Assange
Wikileaks is experiencing more and more difficulties.
Internet service provider Amazon has removed the website that specializes in revealing confidential documents from its servers.
This attitude may hide political pressures after the publication of hundreds of thousands of secret diplomatic notes.
WikiLeaks founder Assange is apparently in England.
In the United States, WikiLeaks is being attacked with increasing force.
The group of cyber activists "Wikileaks" no longer has access to its server hosted so far in America and is now looking for a host in Europe.
Meanwhile, prominent U.S. Senator Joe Lieberman has called on other countries and companies to boycott Wikileaks.
And WikiLeaks founder Julian Assange, who is wanted by Interpol, is likely staying in Britain, according to news reports.
"Wikileaks excluded from Amazon server."
"Freedom of expression in the country of freedom," the cyber activists behind the revelations said on Wednesday via Twitter.
Shortly before, the cyber company, Amazon, had removed Wikileaks documents from its servers.
After the release of secret diplomatic notes, cyber activists turned to Amazon’s Web Service (AWS) in order to achieve the greatest number of access to documents.
WikiLeaks tweeted: "Formidable, our dollars are now being spent on caring for people in Europe."
When freedom of expression poses a problem for Amazon, “they should stop selling books.”
CNN, citing Mr. Liebermann’s office, reported that Amazon banned Wikileaks from using its servers after the investigation by Senator Joe Lieberman’s associates.
The chairman of the Senate committee for the protection of the territory had threatened the Amazon site to orchestrate a boycott against him, reported the British newspaper, "The Guardian".
"I would have liked Amazon to take this action earlier in light of Wikileaks' previous classified information releases," he said.
At the same time, Liebermann called on other countries to refuse the use of servers by the platform.
"WikiLeaks is acting in an illegal, monstrous and unscrupulous manner, putting our national security at risk and endangering our lives around the world," the independent senator said in a statement.
“No company aware of its responsibilities, whether American or foreign, should help Wikileaks disseminate the contents of the stolen documents.”
WikiLeaks founder Assange, who is wanted by Swedish authorities on suspicion of rape, is on Interpol’s wanted list.
According to the London newspaper The Independent, the 39-year-old Australian lives in Britain and Scotland Yard knows exactly where he is.
The cyber-activist has consistently called the Swedish prosecutions orchestrated by his critics intrigues.
WikiLeaks spokesman Kristinn Hrafnsson said in London that threats had been made against the site.
"Calls have even been launched for the murder of Julian Assange."
That is why Assange is particularly concerned for his safety, Hrafnsson said.
This is also why the founder of Wikileaks continues to hide.
Hrafnsson clearly reacted to statements made in North America.
In America, former Republican governor of Arkansas Mike Huckabee has demanded that the person responsible for the Wikileaks revelations be prosecuted and executed for treason.
In Canada, Prime Minister Stephen Harper’s adviser said on television, obviously ironically, that Mr Assange should “be killed” and that Mr Obama could “use a drone.”
Meanwhile, a controversy broke out between the White House and Mr. Assange.
U.S. President Barack Obama’s spokesman Robert Gibbs called it “ridiculous and absurd” that Mr. Assange demanded Secretary of State Hilary Clinton’s resignation if she was responsible for the recently disclosed order to diplomats to engage in espionage activities.
“I don’t know exactly why we need to deal with the opinion of an individual website owner,” Gibbs said.
“Our foreign policy and the interests of this country are far more important than the claims of a website.”
The U.S. government is now completely testing the protection of its databases.
According to a White House statement, Russell Travers, deputy director of the Counter-Terrorism Centre, has been appointed as the leak control officer.
Travers is tasked with implementing "the necessary structural reforms" made indispensable after Wikileaks leaked the diplomatic cables.
The White House also has the will to verify the means by which the entire administration exchanges and protects information.
In addition, the U.S. government has announced that it wants to take care of the safety of dissidents and activists should they ever be threatened by the Wikileaks revelations.
"We have made every effort to get in touch with them," State Department spokesman Philip Crowley said.
"We are ready to protect them if necessary."
The University of Ice
At the Gelato University in Bologna, ice cream confectioners are prepared for the best seasons of the year.
The three-day initiation course for future glaciers was very successful and attracted visitors from all over the world.
By the way, where does all the ice come from?
Glacier and ice machine.
The glacier, that is to say in German the somewhat outdated ice confectioner, makes the cream according to all the rules of the Italian art of making ice.
The ice turbine removes the ice cream from the refrigerated showcase using a spatula, places it in the waffle and then starts selling it.
To find out, one does not need to go to Anzola dell'Emilia in the province of Bologna.
But anyone who wants to know more about ice, can not avoid "Gelato-University" of the Italian firm Carpigiani.
The ice cream maker founded the University of Ice Cream in 2003 so that the ice creams from its machines meet high Italian ideals everywhere.
The three-day introductory course for future glaciers was a great success and attracted visitors from all over the world.
Special courses on chocolate ice cream are also offered over several days, as well as hands-on sessions in the private ice cream parlor.
In the midst of the quarantine crisis, a number of people dream of a new career, others simply risk fulfilling their burning desire on smooth ice.
This time, 40 participants came from 19 countries from all continents, from Brazil to Saudi Arabia to Hungary.
Jacky, an artistic education teacher from California, is a fan of the Slow Food movement and wants to offer a quality European product in the future in the country of Industrial Ice.
Anke from Berlin is a business management consultant and after a few years she wants to draw something unique from this nerve-wracking job.
Two young Egyptian women dream of opening a glacier in Cairo.
A man from Malta and another from Brazil would like to improve the quality of ice cream in their bars, and the Canadian maid came because her children love Italian ice cream.
Master glacier Luciano Ferrari first explains to the participants the ideal characteristics of perfect ice creams.
Determinant is not only good taste, but also silky suppleness and good consistency.
However, Luciano does not forget during the training the cherry on the cake of the national and, in general, southern superstructure: "Italian ice is simply the best: and then it still retains a hell of a dose of romanticism."
The first step in manufacturing seems quite simple.
Luciano pours the basic ingredients, such as milk, cream, milk powder, sugar and stabilizers into a large mixer that heats everything to 85 degrees through an electronic program, then immediately cools to four degrees.
He then opens a faucet installed on the machine: he comes out a pasteurized white cream base, the foundation of all kinds of milk ice cream.
The trainer is immediately beset with the question: Is it possible to make ice using only natural substances without a stabilizer?
How can we give free rein to the personal pleasure of experimentation?
Mr. Luciano warns against being misled by the spirit of time.
Anyone who talks only about ice cream "made from natural ingredients" may have used stabilizers: most often a natural product, for example guar seed flour obtained from guar beans.
It is obviously possible to make ice without using a stabilizer, only it has to be sold within 24 hours, otherwise it collapses and the customer will not chew anything other than ice granules.
Some modifications of the base mass are allowed.
It gets more exciting with the aromas.
Master Luciano makes the difference between the ingredients you buy in the fruit or confectionery department of the supermarket.
In addition, there is powder and pasta.
"the suppliers will all try to give you dozens of flavored ingredients."
"However, you should just try."
Either in the recipes of fruit sorbets with sugar and fresh fruit.
Either in ice creams made from the white base mass which, by adding eggs, becomes a yellow cream and forms, when cocoa powder is added, the basis of all possible chocolate desserts.
Now all participants in the course have to move to the use of ice machines.
Luciano invites them from time to time to make four kinds of ice cream: vanilla, chocolate, mocha and hazelnut with or without eggs in the base mass, with more or less vanilla flavor or other natural ingredients.
The different kinds of fruit ice cream are also subjected to the same experience.
More aromatic substances, more fruit purees: from the point of view of taste, this is not absolutely better.
Hazelnut ice cream does not necessarily have the taste of nuts, when it consists largely of hazelnuts.
Kiwi ice cream, very popular, is made from the group using more fruit, less water and a little less stabilizer.
“Only a balanced blend correctly matches the taste of an ice cream,” says Luciano.
Making ice cream is a calculation exercise: if you use peach puree with a lot of sugar, you need to reduce the amount of sugar in the basic recipe.
A sugar supplement is required for lemon ice cream.
Luciano presents a device with which he determines the sugar content of the different types of fruit (the winemakers use it to measure the degree of Oechsle in grape must).
Fortunately, the tables make calculations easier.
The manufacture of ice does not require as much physical intervention as in the past.
It is not only the automatic mass-making machine that helps.
There is also an apparatus in which the available ice mixture is simultaneously beaten to make it smooth and reduced to negative temperatures.
Despite all the automations, slight breakdowns are not excluded.
The Brazilian Gustavo scrambles with fruit puree from head to toe and, thus, splashes his fellow students when control of the colossal mixing bowl escapes him.
Master Luciano is of the opinion that "such an incident is likely to occur in each class: it is only a matter of time."
Controllers in an ambiguous position
According to some sources, the industry that experiments with the cultivation of genetically modified plants has nucleated the European Food Safety Authority.
This accusation is now made by the Testbiotech expert group, which is considered an independent institute for the assessment of the consequences of biotechnology.
“It sounds like a conspiracy theory, but we did a lot of research,” said Christoph Then, Head of Testbiotech, in Munich on Wednesday.
Some reports indicate that the chairman of the EFSA Group of Experts on Genetically Modified Plants, Harry Kuiper, as well as other EFSA experts are under contract with the Ilsi lobby group.
The latter is financed by groups such as Monsanto, Nestlé or Bayer.
Mr. Kuiper has been instrumental in developing EFSA's testing requirements for genetically modified plants and is therefore clearly in a conflict of interest situation, according to Mr. Then's criticisms.
The provisions drawn up correspond, in paragraphs, to the positions taken by the Ilsi pressure group and thus bear the trade mark of the industry which, at bottom, would be controlled by the authorities established in Parma, Italy.
This is already the second time that Testbiotech has denounced a conflict of interest.
A senior Efsa official has recently joined the Swiss agri-food group Syngenta unconditionally or without a transitional period, and in doing so, she has changed sides.
Not long ago, even the Central German Radio (Mitteldeutsche Rundfunk, MDR) had revealed the existence of personal relations between the European Union authority in charge of control and the industrial lobby, which aroused the suspicions of both the German Federal Environment Agency and MEPs.
However, the EFSA does not accept the existence of any conflict of interest.
One opinion indicates that all reliable data, including industry data, are used as long as they are of good professional quality.
Experts working on behalf of EFSA are not prohibited from making contact with this sector of activity.
But they should make them public.
Mr. Kuiper admits that he works for the U.S.-based International Life Sciences Institute (ILSI).
This body sees itself as a neutral forum for experts from, among others, the fields of science, industry and policy to assess the risks of biotechnology without being on the payroll of a lobby.
In this case, independent experts such as Mr. Then disapprove of the fact that genetically modified plants are accepted without any feeding tests in animals and that the impact of these plants on the environment has not been tested.
"We want to know what are, for example, the incidences of genetically modified maize causes in the field," says Mr. Then.
The current practice is to test only isolated proteins and not all genetically modified plants, which does not provide reliable results.
"If we don't look for risks, how can we find them?" asked Mr. Then in an accusing tone.
This is also the view of Mrs Angelika Hilbeck.
She has been researching genetics since 1994 and is currently working at the Zurich Polytechnic School.
In this region as in the United States, and now also in Europe, the industry sector is increasingly trying to influence or discredit critical scientists.
That is why there are hardly any researchers who are not linked to societies.
In the opinion of the companies, the critical studies would not be published.
Hilbeck says that “the industry controls safety research.”
The trace of stone
Uli Gsell got it, a total of about 400 kilos.
On Monday afternoon, she was standing in front of Stuttgart station with her tube on her back.
There was a demonstration.
It was snowing.
The story is known: In September, the excavators had come and started demolishing much of the north wing.
The world of Stuttgart was no longer the same: Several thousand people protested against the S21 project, the transformation of Stuttgart Central Station into an underground station that will cost billions.
Much of the wing was in ruins when the demonstrations led to the cessation of construction work.
Broken into 6000, 7000 pieces.
The Muschelkalk (the shell limestone) of Crailsheim, a soft and coarse pavement badly built between 1914 and 1920.
Mr. Gsell is a 43-year-old sculptor residing in Ostfildern.
He obtained a few fragments.
"These stones are relics."
"They must not disappear."
He enthusiastically declares: "a modest and cheap rock, simple and terrestrial."
He claimed that by sawing it, he smelled the smoke of cigarettes.
He does not yet know what he will do with this fragment.
The rocks have time.
Uli Gsell, too.
The traces of the Stuttgart stones lead to a former French army ammunition depot in a forest near Tübingen, where Manuel Rongen built his empire of stones.
This 44-year-old man trades in old stones.
He bought all the stones from the demolition in Stuttgart.
“It would be a shame if they were crushed or disappeared in the landfill,” he said in his office in a hut, which was once a guard post.
He said he was insulted and threatened when newspapers reported in September that he had bought the rest of the north wing from the demolition company.
But he negotiated for whole days with the opponents of the S21 project.
And he explained to them that he could do nothing at all to oppose the demolition.
And if it happens, then the most reasonable thing would be to continue using the stones.
Approximately 200 opponents of the S21 project subsequently took one of the stone parallelepiped weighing on average 80 kilos whose value is between 6.50 and 14 Euros.
Some keep it as a souvenir in while also hoping to be able to return it during a reconstruction.
Rongen had acquired 500 tons, 25 full truck loads.
About half is still crammed into the forest, with the rest long since sold.
Owners of gardens, landscape gardeners, Individuals.
They came from everywhere and took everything that could get into the trunk and the trailers.
These Stuttgart scandal stones have long since been transformed into "Mäuerle" or limitations of grass beds.
“By the way, this stone is nothing special,” Rongen said.
"It would not have been this political component."
He enters his all-terrain car, makes the rounds of his vast empire of 20 hectares.
He studied law and later began to study biology before becoming interested in computer science and eventually became a career.
And a stone lover.
It stores 40,000 tons.
He amassed his treasures all over Germany.
He claims to be the greatest merchant of ancient stones.
He's slowing down.
Artfully carved sandstones are laid on the snow.
"In the past, they were part of the Marienbrücke bridge in Dresden."
Elbsandstein, yellow, warm, he says enthusiastically.
"My favorite stone."
He takes the path that goes up through the forest.
He shows a pile of his finger: Red sandstone, formerly part of the Karlsruhe station.
And so on.
"Beautiful travertine."
The parallelepiped was once part of the grandstand of the Neckarstadion in Stuttgart.
Everywhere in the snow of stones and stories, the Cannstatt travertine from the police prefecture, the reddish granite from St. Blasius Cathedral, the tuff from Heilbronn Hospital.
What work, what efforts, what sweat!
When Mr. Rongen thinks that the stones were once carved by hand and moved using simple hoists and carts pulled by oxen, he becomes quite respectful.
“It would be a scandal if such a legacy were torn apart.”
He didn’t get rich, much less rich.
But this carrier now employs 14 people. In addition, stonecutters, a sculptor, a blacksmith, a glassblower and a gardener have settled in the forest.
“We’re working hard, but it’s rewarding,” says the waste recycler.
Soon, he has to go to Cologne.
There are stones to be saved, too.
Talent Struggle to Conquer High Potentials
The counter is experiencing a strong affluence.
16 students are scrambling to buy salmon loaves, tomato sauce, and bleachers.
The Braunschweig Technical University and the car manufacturer Volkswagen invited design and mechanical engineering students to a workshop.
As part of a kind of competition of ideas, they have to talk business about the car of the future with the designers of VW, and, by the way, get to know the firm Volkswagen.
Nowadays, many companies do not hesitate to go hand-in-hand in the competition to find better brains and to engage, like Volkswagen, in multifaceted cooperation with universities.
Their mission: Recruit the most gifted graduates as much as possible in the amphitheatres before they reach the job market and are courted by others.
And since universities do not publish statements about the performance of their students, we try to identify and retain outstanding talent in practical projects.
On the second day of the workshop held at the Technical University of Brauschweig, the automotive group encouraged talents.
A young lady from the staff service shares pens, candy and cards with the Volkswagen logo.
She talks about the calendar of professional internships and student jobs for young talents; she shows them the paths to access the group enclosure.
Nico Selle from the Technical University of Braunschweig is responsible for the project with Volkswagen.
For him, there are reciprocal advantages for both parties: "Students come into contact with this industrial sector and gain experience."
"As for the Volkswagen Group, he can get to know the students, look more closely at the serious candidates and appreciate those who come into play as collaborators."
According to Mr. Saddle, such cooperation is unusual.
What's new is the offensive we're trying to attract students with.
"In the past, the focus was more on the professional project," says Selle.
The struggle for the conquest of the new graduates will become much harsher.
In many industries, companies are no longer able to recruit employees by sorting a number of candidates.
But they must boast their reliability and above all court the highly skilled workforce.
It is mainly graduates from engineering backgrounds who find themselves in an excellent position to negotiate.
According to the German engineering association VDI, more than 40,000 engineering positions remained unoccupied in October.
And according to VDI forecasts, the gap in engineering positions will widen further.
Roman Dykta goes on a talent hunt for KPMG, an audit, accounting and consulting firm.
It organizes expensive events aimed at recruiting talent, such as the KPMG-Race cruise race, a kind of paper rally where competitors must find their way using GPS coordinates.
The company will send eight promising students next year to travel the U.S. in this way.
Participants can also visit KPMG’s subsidiaries and get to know the company.
The person who is to participate is decided in advance after two selection procedures.
Only the cream of the cream of the many candidates will fly to the United States.
According to Dykta, the means used for the quest for high potentials in universities are increasingly important.
"We want to emerge from the crowd thanks to the cruise race."
"For us, a simple cruise was too little"
For the talent hunter Mr. Dykta, the account seems to be there.
"To this day, we have remained in touch with all those who took part in a similar action last year."
"Some of them are about to finish their studies and want to address their requests to our company soon," he says.
Apart from direct taming on campus, small and medium-sized businesses proceed in a very classic way by participating in trade fairs where they engage in the hunt for brains.
"We try to reach graduates by participating in trade shows."
“For example, at the solar technology show,” says Sitha Stübe, director of human resources at Solarworld, a manufacturer of photovoltaic panels.
The Bonn-based company employs around 1500 people in Germany.
Ms. Stübe is aware of the issue of succession.
There are currently 35 positions on the company's website.
"Right now, it's very difficult to fill vacancies."
“It’s expensive and takes a lot of time,” he says.
Another way to establish contact is to go through university professors.
Solarworld has established cooperation with various higher education institutions, for example, the University of Freiburg.
"The professors indicate that the student has the opportunity to do professional internships or to write his final project with us."
Expensive advertising campaigns are announced at solar specialists.
This is why the company tries to advertise by highlighting other qualities: personalized atmosphere, flat hierarchy and easy communication.
“Often, a large group cannot do that,” says Stübe, chief of staff.
For a long time, money has no longer played the leading role in the search for work.
Other determinants are flexible working hours, childcare or good promotion opportunities.
According to a study conducted by the Great Place to Work Institute, Solarworld ranks 55th among the top 100 employers in Germany.
The Institute is an annual honours table of German employers.
To this end, it asks employees about their level of satisfaction with their work and its context while looking at the employee’s framework conditions.
Chief of Staff Ms. Stübe hopes that this placement will enhance the company's image among jobseekers.
“I think candidates rely mostly on external assessments of a potential employer,” she says.
Wolf Reiner Kriegler of the German Academy DEBA (Deutscher Employer Branding Academy, DEBA) advises companies who wish to build a good reputation as an employer by implementing a long-term strategy.
He advises his clients to show more authenticity.
And, according to Mr Kriegler, this means first and foremost taking internal action.
“The best way for an employer to make itself attractive is to go through its own employees,” he says.
This is called, according to the jargon used in the sector, the internal image strategy, i.e. the creation of the employer's brand image within its own workforce.
"satisfied collaborators are the best messengers."
When they treat their employees well and identify with the company, they advertise their employer to their friends and acquaintances on their own.
“It’s like playing in an orchestra,” says Mr. Kriegler.
Obama puts a brake on new oil drilling
There will be no new oil drilling in the Gulf of Mexico off the coast of Florida, the southeastern state of the United States, in the coming years.
The Washington government has issued an equivalent ban and thus definitively overturned its initial plans.
Even off the Atlantic coast, new drilling is currently prohibited.
Home Secretary Ken Salazar made the announcement Wednesday.
The explosion in April of the drilling rig "Deepwater Horizon" is the cause of this strict ban, which must remain in force for at least the next five years.
Faced with the accident, which cost the lives of eleven employees and led to the largest environmental disaster in the United States, President Barack Obama, under pressure from the opposition and this sector of activity, indicated that he was willing to authorize the realization of new drilling in the eastern part of the Gulf of Mexico.
The proponents of this solution want to reduce the dependence of the United States on foreign countries when it comes to the supply of oil.
The question of who bears the responsibility for the devastating oil spill in golf is not, to date, definitively resolved.
The British oil group, which is facing multi-billion dollar claims, is at the center of the charges.
A commission of inquiry set up by Obama is due to present its findings in December.
In October, Interior Secretary Ken Salazar lifted the freeze on the drilling decree after the platform exploded.
As a result of this decision, various oil companies had immediately submitted applications for new drilling projects.
With tighter controls and tougher security guidelines, Obama and Salazar want to prevent another catastrophe.
The competent supervisory authority, which has discredited itself after numerous corruption allegations, is currently undergoing in-depth reforms.
At the same time, Obama announced that he would remove the lucrative tax niches of oil and gas groups.
The players in this sector now publicly warn that the flow rate in the Gulf would be significantly lower than it has been so far.
"The government's goal is to put a brake on the rapid growth of the oil and gas sector," according to the result of a current survey of the sector by the audit firm BDO, ahead of the drilling ban imposed on Wednesday.
In fact, the American Enery Alliance deplores the uncertainty that characterizes this sector: "No one knows exactly what will change with regulation."
Investments in new support projects were deferred until further notice, to the detriment of growth.
The Ogoni country is dry
The water that flows in the rivers is oiled brown; it emits a smell similar to that which exists in the gas station: Due to a leak, billions of liters of crude oil have destroyed the Ogoni country in Nigeria.
Men live on theft, corruption and oil refining.
Celestine Akpobari has a good intention.
“Don’t get exhausted,” the environmental activist tells reporters to calm them: “You still have enough oil mud in front of the water lens today.”
The 37-year-old Nigerian attempted to photograph a young man plunged into muddy water up to his chest, as well as the greasy trail that surrounds him: This scene looks almost beautiful in the burst of rainbow-colored water.
We cannot see that the subsoil is full of brown layers of crude oil.
On the banks of the Bodo-Jetty River, Esther Badom says she once collected shrimp in whole buckets here.
But in the meantime the calm waters have completely dried up.
Five years ago, a huge amount of oil came from an oil pipeline that exploded in the huge swamp.
Fishermen in the nearby small town of Bodo must now row for six hours to reach the fishy waters: The Ogoni country located in the heart of the Niger Delta is considered one of the most polluted regions in the world.
The full extent of the devastation comes to light as we traverse the mangrove swamps crossed by streams.
Instead of clear water, the motorboat splits a crabby brown water. Anyone who dips his hand in it removes it completely covered with oil.
The roots of small mangroves emerge from the ground like liquorice sticks. The isolated palms sadly let their palms hang.
Bird clouds are sought in vain, as they are usually found in wetlands: As soon as the outboard engine stops, a ghostly silence descends on this paradise of yesteryear that resembles a gas station by the smell it emits.
"What is happening here is a war on the environment," says Celestine Akpobari sadly: "Our life is characterized by a permanent danger to health."
The comparison of wars is made.
The region where the Ogoni live has been a battlefield besieged for decades: More than 60 years ago, the first European explorers entered here; the first resistance was organized in the 1980s by the writer Ken Saro-Wiwa. this was later executed. In 1993, the Shell group had to stop its production activities in this region because they had become very dangerous.
Even today, the return to Ogoni country is forbidden to this company: While more than 2 million barrels of black gold are pumped daily thanks to more than 5,000 drilling wells and 7,000 kilometers of pipelines throughout the Delta region, three times as large as Switzerland, the oil fields of Ogoni country are untapped, because the situation is unstable for this tropier.
