The International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) has new indications regarding a nuclear program developed by Syria.
But this country refuses to take a position on this issue, much less submit to the agency's controls.
On the night of 5-6 September 2007, at least four Israeli F-15 I fighter jets attacked a mysterious cubic-shaped building on Syrian territory.
It is located on the bank of the Euphrates; the largest city located nearby is 30 kilometers: it is Dair as-Sur.
His name appears in the IAEA documents, because it is about the reactor that Syria has built with the help of North Korea in stone parallelepiped, hidden in a valley marked by the absence of electricity.
According to a briefing by the US intelligence services, the CIA, dating from the end of April 2008, the current reactor, known as the neighboring locality, el-Kibar, would be well able to produce plutonium, which would make atomic weapons.
On the other hand, this technique has been valid since the 1950s.
The CIA showed a video presentation with fuzzy satellite images.
Through computer-aided animation, it indicated the likely location of each reactor component prior to the destruction of the plant, which represents a miniature copy of the North Korean model of the Yongbyon nuclear power plant.
In addition, she presented the photos showing the building located nearby, even inside it.
It appears that the reactor was about to be commissioned, but it was not yet equipped with fuel rods.
Today, more than three years after the Israeli bombing, we have little more information than at the time, and even, with time, the mystery thickens more and more.
Former U.S. President George W. Bush recently revealed in his memoirs that prior to the attack, the CIA was certain that Syria had built a reactor at al-Kibar, but had little evidence that the country was developing an “active nuclear weapons program.”
Some intelligence officers in Europe prefer to be more cautious about this and speak only of a “supposed reactor,” even if they consider the CIA’s presentation “plausible.”
They lack tangible evidence, as well as the IAEA.
Asked how he ensures he is dealing with a nuclear reactor, a senior U.N. diplomat gave only a laconic response in the summer by claiming that the IAEA had “enough documents to ask questions.”
The Syrians certainly hastily removed the rubble of the “unused military building” and proceeded to methodically flatten the ground.
However, in June 2008, a team of IAEA experts led by former Chief Inspector Oli Heinonen discovered traces of man-made uranium in al-Kibar.
In addition, the IAEA has received through a member state satellite images of commercial providers showing the moment that directly followed the attack. it seems that the latter are more eloquent than those presented by the CIA.
However, these photos are not available on the market because the anonymous sponsor, possibly Israel, acquired them exclusively.
This makes it impossible for the IAEA to establish their authenticity objectively.
Syria has always assured that it had never carried out a secret atomic program and had not built a reactor.
Damascus claims that the uranium found at the site comes from weapons used by Israel.
But the IAEA rejected this argument after the particle analysis, calling it implausible.
Since that time, damasus has refused any discussion about this, as well as about satellite images.
In addition, Syria does not allow controllers to conduct a second inspection at the al-Kibar site and refuses access to the wreckage of the building destroyed by the bomb.
But even Israel keeps a stubborn silence.
Confirming the official position, Ehud Olmert, then Prime Minister in office at the time of the attack, recently said: "We will never comment on this."
Thus, the investigation into this case has dragged on since June 2008 without a result and "becomes increasingly a serious problem of credibility of the Agency", as recognized by a high-ranking Western diplomat on duty at the IAEA headquarters in Vienna, in the end it is a serious violation of the Treaty on the Prohibition of Nuclear Weapons.
The IAEA believes that in order to make progress, the existence of the other three facilities that must have "a functional relationship" with the alleged reactor must be clarified.
So far, the inspectors have not indicated what facilities are here, what their function is or what they are suspected to contain.
According to information published by the newspaper "Süddeutsche Zeitung", they are known within the IAEA respectively as Marj as-Sultan, Masyaf and Iskandariyah also by the names of the neighboring cities.
The independent Institute for Science and International Security in Washington has identified these locations and discovered on satellite images a complex near Masyaf that would most likely be one of the suspicious objects.
It is possible that it is located in a military base or directly next to it; this is exactly why Syria is denying the IAEA inspectors access to all three sites.
In Vienna, it is claimed that Syrians fear that the inspection group is actually spies who would be sent on behalf of the United States by the IAEA to spy on military facilities.
In fact, it was intelligence provided by U.S. secret agents that caught the attention of nuclear inspectors.
The IAEA has information, including satellite photos, indicating that vehicles have shuttled between the three sites and the stone parallelepiped to transport substances.
A senior Western diplomat said in Vienna that at least one of the facilities could be “used for fuel production.”
It would have "no indication of sensitive activities", such as uranium enrichment and reprocessing; processes that are essential for the production of atomic weapons.
This type of reactor certainly works thanks to unenriched uranium.
Nevertheless, there are plausible hypotheses regarding the following fundamental questions: where should uranium have come from and where plutonium needed to make the bomb would have been separated later.
It is not known whether the rubble, which could hide traces of great value, was stored at all three sites.
When the hundreds of trucks loaded with land are gone, no one will have information on where the rubble is stored.
For the IAEA, it is unlikely that Syria had the al-Tibni salt mine, located only a few kilometres from al-Kibar on the other side of the Euphrates, examined in 1998 to see if it could be suitable for the storage of radioactive waste.
Recently analyzing satellite photos taken on behalf of the famed Jane's Intelligence Review magazine, former IAEA inspector Robert Kelley established a link between them and the reactor in question.
Satellite photos show, however, that Syria undertook earthworks at the three suspect sites and moved huge containers when the IAEA began demanding access to those locations.
It is possible that this was a coincidence, but it did not help rule out the suspicions.
It is said in diplomatic circles that the IAEA has spent several months developing a plan for the inspections to be carried out there. This plan was to allow Syria to preserve possible military secrets. Only the time invested shows how much interest the inspectors have in this case.
Meanwhile, Damascus also ignored this proposal.
