Support for democracy in Latin America continues to increase, as does support for private enterprise.
Crime has become a greater concern than unemployment.
And Brazil is seen as more influential than the United States in much of the region.
These are some of the conclusions of the latest Latinobar<0xC3><0xB3>metro survey taken in 18 countries and published exclusively by The Economist.
As the survey has been conducted on a regular basis since 1995, it tracks changes in attitudes in the region.
Two related elements emerge from this year's survey, conducted in September and early October.
The first is the rather sunny mood of Latin America.
The second is the increasing stability of attitudes towards democracy and its main institutions.
Support for democracy has increased significantly in several countries around the South American Pacific (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has averaged 6 per cent per year since 2002, support for democracy has increased from a minimum of 40 per cent in 2005 to 61 per cent this year.
It also grew in Mexico, where the economy recovered after suffering a sharp drop in output last year.
But only about half of respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous countries in the region, are convinced Democrats, lowering the regional average (see Table 2).
Some 44% of respondents in the region expressed satisfaction with the way their country's democracy worked in practice; this is the same number as last year but with a sharp increase from 25% in 2001 (Figure 3).
Some 34 per cent said they had confidence in their country's parliament and 45 per cent in their government, the same as last year in both cases; but up sharply from 2003 (respectively 17 per cent and 24 per cent).
Ten years ago, economic problems in Latin America shook support for democracy.
If this has held up during the global financial crisis, it is certainly due to the fact that many countries in America have suffered only a brief recession and have benefited from a strong recovery.
In addition, a social security network has helped to protect the poor.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty rose only slightly in 2009 and fell again this year to 32 percent.)
However, the mood varies considerably from country to country (see Figure 4).
Brazil’s good economic performance and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz In<0xC3><0xA1>cio Lula da Silva, translates into a widely shared sense of progress.
This is more rare in Mexico and Central America where the recession has been more severe and violent crimes have worsened.
It is only the second time since the survey began that more respondents across Latin America as a whole have cited crime rather than unemployment as the most important problem for their country (see Table 5).
Approximately 31% say that they or one of their relatives have been the victim of a criminal act in the past year; however, this figure is down from 38% last year and is the lowest since 1995.
A stronger economic performance is reflected in increased support for private enterprise and the market economy: about 71% of respondents in the region say private enterprise is indispensable for development, compared with 56% in 2007 (see Chart 6).
Some 58% believe that the market economy is the only system that will make their developed country, up from 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela are of this opinion (and 80% support the private company); even though their left-wing president, Hugo Chavez, expropriates many private companies.
Brazil is the largest leader in the region, mentioned by 19% of respondents (up from 18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, unchanged from last year) and Venezuela (9%, down 11% from last year)
But the United States is considered the most influential country by respondents in Mexico and most of Central America, while Venezuela enjoys this distinction in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
A dirty vote
No one expected a perfect general election in Haiti on November 28.
But it was much worse than the outsiders who wanted to help the country that was hit and in fear.
Ballot boxes and a new ballot were presented, ballots scattered in the gutters, polling stations ransacked and intimidated.
The polling stations opened late at night.
Many Haitians, including many who were displaced in the wake of the January earthquake, wandered in the neighborhood to find where to vote.
Some of them eventually gave up.
A dozen presidential candidates, including several alleged favorites, denounced the fraud and called for the election to be cancelled.
Protests, sometimes violent, have exploded across the country.
Nevertheless, Edmond Mulet, the senior official in Haiti at the United Nations, considers the event "a fairly good election in many ways".
Observers from the Organization of American States and the Caribbean Community cautiously stated that they “did not believe that these irregularities, however serious, had necessarily invalidated the process.”
In other words, the show continues.
The electoral authority, whose opponents are indebted to René Préval, outgoing unpopular president, and his candidate, Jude Célestin, must announce the preliminary results on December 7.
The second round is scheduled for January.
All hope in the election is not lost.
The two opposition candidates, Michel Martelly, a rap musician, and Mirlande Manigat, a former first lady, withdrew from their initial call for the vote to be declared null and void.
But there may be problems if Mr. Célestin, who has little or no discernible support among voters, is declared by the electoral authority as having reached the second toura reaches the second round.
With a cholera epidemic raging, and more than 1 million earthquake survivors still living in tents, there was fear that participation would be.
In this case, many Haitians wanted to vote but were prevented from doing so because of the disorganization.
Nearly 250,000 identity cards, needed to vote, were not yet distributed shortly before the election.
The stakes are important.
Donors see the election of a popular and legitimate government as an important step in Haiti’s reconstruction.
And so, it is clear, Haitians do it themselves.
The tip of the feet towards the center
In the weeks after she suddenly became a widow, Cristina Fern<0xC3><0xA1>ndez, President of Argentina, enjoyed a wave of public sympathy that improved her approval rating by 20 points, to more than 50%; this is her highest level since she was elected in 2007.
Turning this into a successful campaign for a second term in an election next year may depend on Ms Fern<0xC3><0xA1>ndez’s choice, visibly in mourning, that she would abandon or not abandon the intransigence of her late husband, predecessor and former political partner, Néstor Kirchner.
And, in this regard, the signs remain confused.
Kirchner, who continued to manage economic policy even after his wife succeeded him as president, used to develop budgets that underestimated tax revenues, economic growth and inflation.
This allowed the first couple to spend the extra income at will.
Mrs. Fern<0xC3><0xA1>ndez's government lost its majority in Congress last year, on paper.
But the opposition is divided, and the situation has sunk into disarray following Kirchner's death from a heart attack on 27 October.
Some of the dissident members of the ruling Peronist movement rallied with Ms. Fern<0xC3><0xA1>ndez.
But after chaotic sessions (where one MP slapped one of his peers in the face and others accused the government of corruption), Congress does not have to approve the 2011 budget.
“I’m not going to argue,” the president said.
Currently, the 2010 budget will be implemented next year, leaving the president even more room to spend at will.
The economy is largely overheating: it is likely to grow by nearly 9% this year.
The official inflation rate now stands at 11.1% but many private estimates and wage demands from unions see this figure close to 30%.
Mr. Kirchner, who took office in 2003 when Argentina feared an economic collapse, made growth and poverty reduction a priority, rather than controlling inflation.
He refused to deal with the IMF, harassed the private sector and purged the INDEC, the statistical office, which falsified official inflation statistics.
Can Mrs Fern<0xC3><0xA1>ndez now moderate these policies?
She called for talks between private companies and union leaders.
And its officials say they want to limit wage increases next year to 18%.
The economy was spurred by high world prices of Argentina's agricultural exports.
But inflation eroded the growth boost following a sharp devaluation in 2002.
Perhaps that is why Mrs Fern<0xC3><0xA1>ndez is showing signs of wanting to restore Argentina's financial relations with the rest of the world.
This year, the government reached an agreement with bondholders who had refused a previous forced debt restructuring for which Argentina had not settled its maturities in 2001.
Now Ms Fern<0xC3><0xA1>ndez looks to be editing towards an agreement with creditor governments grouped in the Paris Club, to which it owes some $6.7 billion.
The Kirchners have always insisted that this could not involve surveillance by the IMF, as is customary.
But last month, Economy Minister Amado Boudou announced that the Fund would provide "technical assistance" to design a new national consumer price index; which looks like a prelude to the remediation of the INDEC.
It is unclear whether Ms Fern<0xC3><0xA1>ndez wants to remain in politics beyond the end of her term, now that her husband is no longer by her side.
If it does, it needs to gain support from the middle class, among whom Kirchnerism is highly advocated.
When the Argentinians return from their summer vacation in March, the wave of sympathy for her will have receded.
If she wants to win another election, she will have to decide whether or not to quietly repudiate many of her husband’s policies.
A half-hour for China
Taiwanese voters have moved towards a kind of closer union with the continent.
What does Taiwan think of its big brother on the other side of the strait?
More than 7.5 million voters ran on November 27, or 70% of eligible people, to elect mayors and municipal councillors in five urban districts, as part of what is considered a general assessment by President Ma Ying-jeou.
Mr. Ma himself has become a substitute for feelings towards the continent, having forged innovative business ties, including a partial free trade pact, in the largest reorganization of relations with China proper since 1949.
Mr. Ma passed the test, but just right.
Although his Kuomintang (KMT) party won three of the five mayoralties, it failed to win a majority of the votes.
Instead, the Democratic Progressive Party (DPP), which leaned toward full independence from Taiwan, won nearly 50% of all votes for the KMT by 45%.
If it had been a presidential election, Mr. Ma would be in trouble.
Since he was elected two years ago, his party's voting share has fallen by about 8%.
For the first time, the DPP attracted voters, even with the KMT in the municipal councils.
The event unveiled most of the main topics of the Taiwanese elections, including loud country trucks and mass rally flags with girls dancing in minimal attire.
An attempt at mandatory mysterious assassination was also perpetrated.
Sean Lien, son of Lien Chan, honorary president of the KMT, conducted an election tour for a KMT candidate on the eve of the election.
A man from the crowd shot the young Mr. Lien, purely through the face, wounding him and killing a passerby.
Strangely, it was not determined whether the shooter wanted to harm Mr. Lien or settle a dispute with the candidate.
In any case, says Tsai Ing-wen, the leader of the PDP, the murder had an impact on the election by directing suspicion on the DPP and turning voters to the KMT.
Perhaps the biggest winner in the election was China.
It was striking how much the question of the mainland itself was absent.
Instead, candidates toyed with plans for public housing and job creation.
Taiwan usually enjoys its de facto independence and hates China’s military threat.
Thus, the KMT tends to avoid paralyzing its ties with the Beijing government.
But this time, the DPP also refrained from stoking anti-Chinese sentiment.
This is the answer to a new realization that Chinese companies are indispensable to Taiwan’s economic survival.
Ma, for his part, demanded confirmation as to whether his China policy was acceptable to the Taiwanese majority.
It is to be expected that the Beijing government will continue to provide trade facilities, in line with its strategy to lure Taiwan back into the fold.
China wasted no time sending a negotiator to Taipei to hold a summit on investment protection and medical cooperation.
Of course, it would also like to see political integration; but let’s start from the beginning.
It is better to wait for this after the 2012 presidential election.
The DPP has reinvented itself anyway.
Two years ago, his former leader, Chen Shui-bian, was sent to prison on corruption charges.
President from 2000 to 2008, he was a provocateur in favor of explicit independence.
But a new generation of moderates has emerged under the leadership of Ms. Tsai and the PDP is working hard to attract professionals and young people.
Ms. Tsai was hailed as a DPP presidential candidate, as Su Tseng-chang, who served under Mr. Chen.
Their party is doing its best to show that he too can engage with Beijing.
Ms. Tsai announced plans for a panel of experts to act as a point of contact between the DPP and China, provided that their talks can take place without preconditions.
Tsai tells the Taiwanese public that her party presents a "trustworthy alternative" to Ma's hasty approach to China.
Mr. Chen seems exasperated by this change.
In a statement released from his cell, he said the PDP candidates would have scored better if they had insisted that Taiwan is a separate country.
He even ordered Mr Su, a pragmatist, not to run for the presidency.
Even without Mr. Chen's intervention, the DPP will have a hard time choosing between its potential candidates.
The KMT must make an introspection of itself.
Mr. Ma's assessments were low; despite dizzying economic growth, the KMT candidates did not want to campaign with him.
Its unpopularity seems to be largely due to unemployment and the widening gap between rich and poor.
A spokesman for the KMT said its cabinet and local offices would be revamped.
The good results of the PDP suggest that Taiwan’s support for the rapprochement is limited.
At the same time, most Taiwanese see economic integration with China as inevitable.
According to Antonio Chiang, a prominent columnist, "the point of no return has already passed."
Grammy Award Nominations: Jazz Singer Esperanza Spalding is a Surprise Selected in the "Best New Artist" Category
Perform at the request of a president, and people are required to take notice of it.
Esperanza Spalding, the 26-year-old jazz bassist and singer handpicked by President Obama to perform at his 2009 Nobel Peace Prize ceremony, marked one of this year's Grammy Awards surprises with a major nomination in the category of "Best New Artist."
Considering Spalding is a well-known figure on the jazz scene since his 2008 album, "Esperanza", the nomination remains somewhat mysterious but it is consistent with the Grammy Award rules that an artist must not release more than three albums before recording; which "establishes the public identity of this artist."
His ambitious 2010 album, "Chamber Music Society", certainly marked a step forward and, given his slightly engaging vocal style, his skillful hand of pop and funk and his Latin influences, it is possible to draw at least one dotted line at Spalding compared to Norah Jones's glittering success in 2003, the closest equivalence to the Grammy Award-winning finalists.
Elsewhere, Grammy Award voters have rightly honored Vijay Iyer Trio's "Historicity" in the "instrumental album" category, a ride on an invigorating thrill of a record that was one of last year's top favorites.
