Wild Darcy James Argue's Secret Society, familiar with steampunk, has gained some well-deserved recognition in the big ensemble category; competing with the rich chamber-jazz of Billy Childs Ensemble and the eternal adventurer Dave Holland whose live byte's "Pathways" album was a fine example of this bassist's democratic hand as a bandleader.
Grammy Award Nomination: Michael Daugherty and Steve Mackey Lead in Classic Categories
The classic nominations for the 53rd Annual Grammy Awards feature a mix of landscapes of musicians and composers from around the world.
Leading the nominations are Michael Daugherty's "Deus Ex Machina" for piano and orchestra, with five "yes"; and Steve Mackey's "Dreamhouse", an electric orchestral work, with three "yes".
Among the nominees with ties to Southern California is Estonian composer Arvo Pärt for his Symphony No. 4, "Los Angeles", a work that was commissioned by the Los Angeles Philharmonic and opened the Walt Disney Concert Hall in 2009.
The Madolin Concerto by Los Angeles-based composer Avner Dorman is also vying for an award.
Classical nominations are divided into 13 categories covering orchestral, opera, choral and solo recordings.
A category for the classic producer of the year features five nominees: Blanton Alspaugh, David Frost, Tim Handley, Marina and Victor Ledin and James Mallinson.
Nominations for the classic album are Bruckner's Symphony No. 3 and No. 4 of the Royal Concertgebouw Orchestra; Daugherty's "Deus Ex Machina" and "Metropolis Symphony" of the Nashville Symphony Orchestra; Steven Mackey's "Dreamhouse" of the Boston Modern Orchestra Project and Synergy Vocals; "Sacrifice" of the "Chorustratum" and "Deus Ex Machina".
In the opera category, the nominees are "Lulu" by Berg of the Orchestra of the Royal Opera House, "Marc Antonio e Cleopatra" by Adolf Hasse of the Ars Lyrica Houston; "L'Amour de Far" by Kaija Saariaho of the Deutsches Symphonie-Orchester Berlin; "The Enchanted Wanderer" by Rodion Shchedrin and "The Enchanted Wanderer" by Rodion Maridrin of the Choir.
The composers who are in place for the Grammy Awards for contemporary composition count Pärt for Symphony No. 4, Daugherty for "Deus Ex Machina", Hans Werner Henze for "Appassionatamente Plus", Magnus Lindberg for "Graffiti" and Shchedrin for "The Wanderer Enchanted".
Pärt's Symphony No. 4 premiered at Disney Hall in January 2009 in a performance recorded by the Los Angeles Philharmonic, conducted by Esa-Pekka Salonen.
The work of about 30 minutes is nicknamed "Los Angeles" and is dedicated to the former oil magnate Mikhail Khodorkovsky, imprisoned in Russia.
Dorman's "Mandolin Concerto" was nominated for his solo instrumental performance with an orchestra.
The Los Angeles composer said he wrote the 15-minute work specifically for mandolin performer Avi Avital, who played the concerto with the Metropolis Ensemble, based in New York.
“I wrote it using sounds from the Middle East and a large number of scales and rhythms from North Africa,” Dorman said in a telephone interview.
Conductor Pierre Boulez, 85, received a nomination in the orchestral performance category for conducting the Chicago Symphony Orchestra in a recording of Stravinsky's works.
Instrumental soloists who received nominations include pianists Nelson Freire and Marc-André Hamelin; organist Paul Jacobs; violinist Julia Fischer; and harpist Sarah Schuster Ericsson.
This year, there are only nominees vocalist-soloists; here they are: Anne Sofie Von Otter, Cecilia Bartoli, Lucie Duchonov<0xC3><0xA1>, Vivica Genaux and Measha Brueggergosman.
In the category of classical mixes, soprano Jessye Norman received a nomination for her recording "Roots: My Life, My Song"
The Temecula Mosque project won the approval of the planning commission.
A mosque project in Temecula received unanimous support from the local planning commission after more than five hours of public testimony, often passionate.
Critics attacked the project by claiming that it promoted both terrorism and traffic jams.
But the commissioners ruled Wednesday night that the new religious center complied with local laws and would be aesthetically impressive.
"Many good people have come to support it: Christians, Jews, Baha'is, you mention it," Hadi Nael, president of the Islamic Center of Temecula Valley, said Thursday morning.
"I'm proud of that, as an American citizen."
"This shows that justice prevails."
“The opposition is really minimal,” he added.
"They just have very strong voices."
"We have good people in this valley."
The session began at 6 p.m. and lasted until almost midnight with, most of the time, people speaking out for or against the center, at roughly equal speaking time, according to the Press-Enterprise.
The debate continued on the newspaper’s website.
“There is no more America,” one speaker wrote.
"This is another planet of monkeys with Miss Liberty dead in the sand."
"America has fallen."
Planned Islamic centers have also sparked protests in other parts of the country, including at Ground Zero, the site of the September 11, 2001 attacks in New York City.
Imam Mahmoud Harmoush denounced the violence in the Temecula Valley.
Her congregation of the order of 135 families has co-existed without incident in Riverside County for years but she wanted a larger and better space than the warehouse she rented on a property shared with a water filtration system manufacturer.
The new 24,943-square-foot mosque with Mediterranean-style architecture would consist of two minarets and rise to 43 feet high.
It would occupy a site of 4.32 hectares on the Nicolas road about two miles east of the Chaparral High School.
Opponents can still appeal against this project to the city council.
An arsenic-tolerant microbe raises the possibility of new types of life on Earth, or elsewhere.
The discovery of a strange bacterium, which can use arsenic as one of its nutrients, widens the scope for finding new forms of life on Earth and perhaps beyond.
Although researchers have discovered the unusual bacteria here on Earth, they say it shows that life has possibilities beyond the major elements that have been considered essential.
"This body has a double capacity."
"It can develop either with phosphorus or with arsenic."
"That's why it's very special, even if it's far from being a really 'foreign' life form," said Paul Davies C. W. of Arizona State University, co-author of the report in Thursday's online edition of the journal Science.
Six major elements have long been considered essential for life: carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulfur.
But researchers have found that the bacterium, discovered in Mono Lake, California, is able to continue to grow after replacing phosphorus with arsenic.
"We're wondering what's still possible," said Ariel Anbar D. of Arizona State University, co-author of the report.
The discovery is important in the search for life beyond Earth because researchers need to be able to recognize life, to know what life looks like, says Anbar.
The study focuses on a microbe found on Earth.
However, the announcement of a press conference to discuss it, which did not divulge the details of the finding, has generated widespread speculation on the Internet that the report could divulge the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
That was not the case.
The discovery "shows that, in other planetary environments, organisms may be able to use other elements to actuate biochemistry and that the "standard" set of elements, which we deem absolutely necessary for life, may not be fixed," commented Charles Cockell, a professor at the Institute for Planetary and Spatial Scientific Research, Open University, Milton Keynes, UK.
Cockell wasn't on the research team.
"This work is new because it shows the substitution of one element to another in fundamental biochemistry and biochemical structure," added Cockell.
It was not an accidental discovery.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA's Institute of Astrology, who led the study, chose Mono Lake because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar; thus, she speculated that a microbe exposed to both substances might be able to substitute for each other.
“Arsenic is toxic mainly because its chemical behavior is really similar to that of phosphorus.”
"As a result, organisms have difficulty distinguishing these elements separately."
“But arsenic is different enough that it doesn’t work exactly like phosphorus; it gets inside and sort of gums the work of our biochemical machine,” Anbar explained.
The researchers collected the bacterium known as GFAJ-1 and exposed it to increasing concentrations of arsenic to which it was able to adapt and grow.
The microbe grows better with phosphorus but the fact that it can live with arsenic instead raises the possibility that a form of life using arsenic can occur naturally, either elsewhere on Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said the idea that arsenic could be replaced by phosphorus was not new; but nothing ever showed that it could work.
Arsenic was more common in the early days of Earth's existence, she says; thus, researchers hypothesized that early life forms could have used it.
This suggests that there might be other ways to form life, not just the way life on Earth was formed at first,” said Foster, who was not part of Wolfe-Simon’s research team.
The research was funded by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Institute of Health.
The last two stolen show dogs were found in Compton.
The other two show dogs out of four stolen from outside a motel in Bellflower have been found, Los Angeles County sheriffs announced Thursday.
The four show dogs — two Welsh akitas and two Pembroke corgis — disappeared Tuesday when someone stole the Chevrolet Express pickup truck in which they had spent the night outside a Bellflower 6 motel, authorities said.
Two of the dogs were recovered Wednesday afternoon and the other two were found late Wednesday evening, Los Angeles County Sheriff’s Department spokesman Steve Whitmore said.
“The good news is that dogs are doing well,” Whitmore says.
“They are in good shape.”
"They have been returned to their rightful owners."
Whitmore declined to say exactly where the dogs had been found, in which neighborhood, and what the circumstances of their discovery were.
"An investigation is underway."
“We don’t want to say it,” Whitmore said.
"We follow orders."
Dog owners Kristina Rickard and David Peek could not be reached for comment Thursday.
They were reunited Wednesday afternoon with their two Akitas at a county animal shelter in Downey.
Sheriff's deputies found the van and the two dogs separately in Compton.
The Akitas - Trace, a 3-year-old male, and Didi, a 10-month-old female - were safe and sound, authorities said.
But Bunny and Peter, the corgis Rickard and Peek had planned to show at regional competitions this week on behalf of Japanese dog owners, were missing until their discovery Wednesday night.
Peek and Rickard, who live in Redding, are in town this weekend as part of Long Beach's "AKC/Eukanuba" national championship, where they planned to host Trace.
The other dogs were expected to compete in other events planned in the days leading up to the "AKC/Eukanuba" exhibition, Peek told The Times on Wednesday.
Southern California is one of the stops on the couple’s nearly a month-long dog show tour.
On Monday night, Peek and Rickard checked into the motel.
They often stay in motels and park their van outside, right next to their bedroom window.
They took three other dogs — a Boxer puppy, a Parson Russell terrier, and a Breton Spaniel — who stayed with them in the motel room.
But they left the Akitas and the corgis, with thicker fur, in the van where it would be cooler.
They opened the windows a little, so that the dogs could have fresh air.
Peek and Rickard reported the theft of the van at 6 a.m. on Tuesday.
Peek said they would offer a reward to anyone who could lead them to the corgis, equipped with an implanted microchip to identify them.
It is unclear whether a prize was awarded on Thursday.
The lion is ready to blush again, the restructuring of MGM is waiting for the final green light of the court
After 18 months of turbulence and uncertainty, MGM finally got the green light to start all over again.
A New York federal bankruptcy judge on Thursday officially praised the "pre-packed" plan by creditors that would wipe out about $5 billion of the debt; paving the way for the 86-year-old entertainment company to focus its efforts on producing and distributing movies and television shows.
With Thursday’s decision that the plan meets the requirements of the U.S. bankruptcy code, no legal obstacles remain before MGM to resurface under the tutelage of Entertainment Spyglass founders Gary Barber and Roger Birnbaum, who will become the CEOs of what will be a lightened studio.
Staff will be reduced to approximately 320 out of 400 initially.
MGM will not actually emerge from Chapter 11 until JPMorgan Chase has concluded a $500 million credit facility to fund MGM’s new operations and productions.
It is currently distributed under license by the investment bank, which is itself worth $75 million, and is expected to be funded by mid-December.
The process of restructuring the studio began in May 2009 when investment bank Moelis & Co. was hired to advise management on how to place its finances as it did not have the means to pay interest in the amount of $300 million per year.
In August, CEO Harry Sloan was replaced by Stephen Cooper, a former CEO of Enron and a recovery expert known for his work at Krispy Kreme Doughnuts.
Moelis and Cooper’s attempts to solve MGM’s financial difficulties and satisfy the studio’s more than 140 creditors took much longer than expected.
After several months of discussions, the parties agreed, at the end of 2009, to put the company up for sale.
However, the auction attracted few bidders, none of whom were willing to pay the additional $2 billion that the creditors were looking for.
In the spring of this year, everything had to be done again as the MGM team began working on a restructuring plan that, after months of internal disagreements and debates, was finally approved by creditors in late October.
When MGM officially came out of bankruptcy in the following weeks, the Moelis and Cooper companies received multi-million dollar bonuses for their work.
Moelis & Co., which has already secured $1.2 million, will receive a payment of $9.5 million.
Cooper’s companies, which raised $375,000 per month for their corporate management services, will receive a “success premium” of $4 million.
Barber and Birnbaum plan to restart production on MGM, which released only one film this year, and put together an annual list of seven or eight films that would be released starting in 2012.
They also plan to co-finance two films based on “The Hobbit,” with Warner Bros.
The studio must enter into a separate loan between $265 million and $275 million to fund its share in these two films, which must be directed by Peter Jackson.
Investor Carl Icahn, who holds about 18% of MGM’s debt, has attempted to merge the studio with Lions Gate Entertainment, where he is the main shareholder.
However, recent discussions between the two companies have not resulted in an agreement.
Tech toys to keep your gift budget in balance
While the top candidate for this year’s most wonderful toy is the IPAD, followed, perhaps, by Microsoft’s video game system, Kinect, both can make a major breach in your gift budget.
Consider that, for the price of an iPad, you can buy five BMX bikes for $99 and that a Kinect game costs the same price as 10 classic beaded jump ropes, or about 48 boxes of Play-Doh.
But there are ways to keep your gift budget in balance.
Recently, I visited three national toy vendors – Wal-Mart, Toys “R” Us and BJ’s Wholesale Club – to see the electronic toys I could buy for under $80.
It is clear that Moore's Law has evolved, this year's tech toy is likely to have more strength; while costing the same price if not a little less, compared to last year.
Also, while there are generally fewer new toys associated with websites, two of the best known of this type, Webkinz and Club Penguin, have more offers.
And button battery toys are on the rise, as well as rechargeable battery toys.
Here are some recommendations.
(All prices are from Toys "R" Us unless otherwise noted.)
Sing-a-ma-jigs (Mattel, $13 for 3 years and older) are stuffed toys the size of a guinea pig that sing a note when you squeeze them on the belly.
One pressure is equal to one note, and a second allows you to compose a song.
If you buy several, they will sing in harmony.
Attention: once you start pressing, you can no longer stop.
To combine singing with dancing, Dance Mickey Star (Fisher-Price, $60 for 2 years and more) is the best choice.
Inspired by last year’s Elmo Live technology, the 14-inch animatronic doll plays turn-based games like Simon Says and can do the lunar dance thanks to its innovative articulated feet with wheel lock.
The children who tested the toy use Mickey as a dance instructor while their parents complain about a lack of volume control.
If you are a child of the 80s, you will remember Alphie, one of the first computerized educational toys.
It’s back (Hasbro/Playskool, $40 for 3 years and more), with a backpack filled with quiz playing cards designed to turn a car ride into a session with a self-correction and a valve filing cabinet.
If you are suspicious when your child holds your smartphone, here are three standalone alternatives.
The VTech Mobigo ($60, for 3 to 8 year olds) is the cheapest and easiest to use, with a qwerty keyboard, although the games do not educate as effectively as the Explorer Leapster ($70, for 3 to 12 year olds), it is the first major revision of the Leapster range, with a newer and brighter screen.
No version is compatible with the old cartridges.
Fisher-Price's iXL ($90, for ages 3-7) uses an iTunes-like system to offer games and e-books and has an SD card input that allows you to view family photos.
Finally, Scrabble Flash ($30, Hasbro, for ages 8 and older) is a set of five blocks just larger than a matchbox, each with its own LED display.
The goal is to form words by placing the blocks in line before time runs out, this is ideal for an impromptu spelling contest.
Increasingly, toys have a kind of online connection.
Based only on their presence in toy stores, the two largest are Webkinz and Club Penguin.
To buy your child an online Penguin Club pet, for example, you can get a Disney Club Penguin 2"Mix 'N Match Figure Pack, $5, for ages 6 to 12) which includes a coin marked with a hidden code.
When you redeem the code online, your child receives enough Club Penguin store credits for two items of choice.
It can be roller skates or a pet toy Puffle.
Slightly larger than the hair at the end of your toothbrush, Hexbug Nano ($10, for 5 years and more) is the latest button battery micro-robots.
The fake beast moves quickly on 12 vibrating silicone pastes in random directions.
It’s fun to make a maze of blocks to see if she can find her way through.
