Federal prosecutors are clearly afraid to take up arms, said Melanie Sloan, the general manager of citizens for accountability and ethics in Washington, a advocacy group that received several complaints against Mr. Ensign in the case.
"This basically says high-ranking government officials can now assume the laws don't apply to them," she added.
Paul Coggins, Ensign's senior lawyer, said in an interview that he received a phone call Monday from a prosecutor at the Department of Justice and a follow-up the next day, telling him that the department was not looking for charges against his client.
