Can civility bring divisions closer together?
After a campaign marked by invective and negativity, a minimum of civility erupted in Washington this week.
Is it a harbinger of genuine bipartisan cooperation forward or an illusory moment before the rapid return to partisan struggle in the capital?
Tuesday’s meeting between President Obama and congressional leaders produced no breakthroughs on the big issues that need to be addressed during the “lame duck” session.
But obviously, there has at least been a polite discussion about the differences of the two sides as well as about acknowledging their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than another episode where each side wanted to score points.
Wednesday’s public meeting of the president’s deficit committee was just as civilized, despite the political differences that remain between members.
It seems clear that the close interaction of several months has created mutual respect transcending the ideological divide; but that, however, still divides the members.
This is hardly enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
The two sides are now in a period of mutual trial and testing for signs of cooperation and compromise, while trying to gauge the limits of public opinion and voters' patience for a renewed partisan war.
That is why Tuesday's meeting and subsequent comments from participants revealed a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and Republicans are too great and too deep to suggest a rapid climate change that has existed over the past two years.
Whether it’s taxation, spending, health care or rights, both sides remain miles away.
Yet the November election had moderated Washington, at least in the short term.
“There is no doubt that things have changed on the tone,” said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official, now at the Center for Ethics and Public Policy.
“This is inevitable after the election.
The elections arouse partisan passions and then they fade away.
That's good."
On some issues, including those on the agenda of the "lame duck" session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush’s tax cuts will expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favor of that.
Both sides want to find a way to preserve some or all of them, permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, a compromise can be envisaged on the extension of unemployment benefits, if only because Republicans cannot afford to give the impression that they are in favour of tax cuts for the rich, while at the same time denying unemployment benefits to unemployed workers.
After Tuesday's meeting at the White House, more optimism looms over a possible agreement on the issues raised during the session on the "lame duck", with the ratification of the "New START" pact.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation on the most pressing issues of the Lame Duck session will not necessarily lead to a better understanding between the two parties when the 112th Congress meets in January.
Instead, he says, a period of disagreement is likely, if not inevitable.
“Once the things that need to be done are done, psychology in the short term will return to one of the confrontations,” he said.
Wehner also expressed his widely shared skepticism that civility would lead to genuine cooperation.
“I consider most of what’s going on between now and 2012 to be a pre-show or a shadow-boxing compared to the main event of 2012,” he said.
The reasons for this are closely related to the composition of the new Republican majority in the House and the voters present at the tea that contributed to its creation.
However, Republican leaders are aware of the dangers if they go too far, they know that they must try to live up to their promises to cut public spending and repeal the new health care law.
These partisan positions are already clear in the early reactions to the deficit committee's recommendations, which include reforming the tax code and raising certain taxes, raising the retirement age and cutting spending.
Co-chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have chosen one of the toughest tasks in Washington and have, in their own words, imposed the deficit issue on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the 18-member committee to issue their plan as an official recommendation, and they struggled to reach that number.
The greatest resistance remains among the group's elected officials, suggesting that there are, at least today, few reasons or compromises on tax issues.
Galston foresees two phases in the fighting between the White House and Republicans in Congress.
The first will come next year in the form of partisan clashes, given that Republicans are challenging Obama on budget, taxes and health care; and then followed by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What would be the cause of the change?
The public opinion.
There is ample evidence that, despite the partisan spirit of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see both parties working together.
If the confrontation leads to an impasse, as in 1995, then both parties will closely observe the reaction of the public.
The one who will be judged at a loss will have to change course and find compromises.
But that would still be an optimistic view.
The partisan spirit and polarization are greater today than they were in the mid-1990s and there seems to be a greater ideological gap between Obama and Congressional Republicans than there was then between President Bill Clinton and Republicans.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as a mere prelude to a more consequential election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civility exposed this week could be enjoyed by many Americans.
But it will take much more effort on both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
