Sport and fraud of the law
The tricks similar to that of Alonso and Ramos against Ajax demonstrate ingenuity but not the will to escape a sanction.
The expulsion in principle by two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) during the November 23 match against Ajax in the Champions League has caused a lot of ink on the anti-sports character of such behavior and whether both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As we know, a few minutes before finishing the game (which their team was already clearly winning), both players deliberately lost time when they made mistakes in determining the referee to show them the second yellow card.
Thus, and given that Real Madrid will eventually be the leader of its group, both players will complete the regulatory sanction during the next match of the barrage match against Auxerre and will be able to move without cards to the next phase.
Finally, the UEFA discipline committee sanctioned the team's coach, José Mourinho, with two matches and different economic sums to the players involved.
Provoking a yellow card in circumstances like this or similar is not a new practice, but rather common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, the unwritten but followed rules of this sport.
Part of the debate that emerged in the related case is due to the fact that this had as protagonist a team of the entity of Real Madrid (who in his anthem displays the nobility and honor and who on past occasions has condemned to a fine to his players for similar acts) and to the dramatization orchestrated, it seems, by Mourinho, who adds a more hila.
In any case, the debate asks whether this type of behaviour is not expressly prohibited by the regulation and contradicts the principles of sport, that is to say, whether these actions commit legal fraud, because they are actions that respect the sporting regulation, but seem to evade its meaning.
The question is to examine the type of harm they cause to the sporting spirit.
One of the assets that includes the sporting spirit is the physical integrity of the opposing players, an aspect that with these actions has not been endangered, that is, there has been no violent play.
Another of these assets that is alluded to with the correct game is to prevent the team of offending players from unfairly profiting from the opposing team, which is not the case either.
However, the paradoxical fact of the action of Real Madrid players is that it does not accommodate what is normally characterized as cheating or fraud of the law, because its violation of the rules was not carried out in secret to try to avoid the sanction, but their action precisely tried to be as obvious as possible to receive the penalty of the referee.
They waited and gladly accepted the sanction.
Another issue is the type of benefit that offenders obtain from the intentional faults examined.
Here it seems necessary to observe that one does not put in a situation of disadvantage to the rival and one does not get an advantage in the same match either, because obviously the result of the action assumes the fact of leaving their own team with fewer players.
And it’s not a useful strategy for the next game either, because the club couldn’t count on these players.
Obviously the advantage lies in the fact that the players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future match.
But this is a long-term advantage, with some degree of indeterminacy, because the team could be eliminated suddenly and apart from that, with this action the players complete a penalty game and move on to the second round of cards, in which the suspension due to the accumulation of cards occurs with one less than in the first round.
So, climbing the ladder, it's not so clear that it's an advantage.
Ultimately, these actions are not contrary to the sporting spirit, which nevertheless includes making strategic decisions that promote the maximum benefit of what the rules allow.
In our case, the players did not act to avoid the application of the sanction (it would indeed be a clear case of fraud of the law), otherwise they chose instead the moment in which they submitted to it.
They made a strategic decision without evading the penalty or running away from it.
Even though the line between genius and fraud of the law is widespread, on this occasion I think we had a clear case of genius.
The controversy, it seems to me, arises because of two factors: because there have been two self-expulsions and because of the way of transmitting the director to provoke them.
The evil caused to the principles of sport by these actions is not so much ethical as aesthetic.
