Vengeful hackers and spies in diligence
The WikiLeaks case has a double value.
On the one hand, it turns out to be an apparent scandal, a scandal that appears as a scandal only in the face of the hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it heralds profound changes at the international level, and predicts a future dominated by regression.
But let's proceed in order.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation that every file made up of a secret service (of any nation) is composed exclusively of press clippings.
The "extraordinary" American revelations about Berlusconi's sexual habits only report what for months could be read in any newspaper (except those of which Berlusconi owns), and Gaddafi's sinisterly caricatured profile was long ago for cabaret artists sketch material.
The rule that secret files should only be composed of new ones that are already known is essential to the dynamics of the secret services, and not only in this century.
If you go to a bookstore devoted to esoteric publications, you will see that each work repeats (on the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Ch<0xC3><0xA2>teau, the Templars or the Rose-Croix) exactly what was already written in the previous works.
And this not only because the author of occult texts does not like to do unpublished research (nor does he know where to look for news about the non-existent), but because those who devote themselves to occultism only believe what they already know, and who reconfirms what they had already learned.
This is the mechanism of Dan Brown's success.
Same goes for secret files.
The whistleblower is lazy, and lazy (or limited-minded) the head of the secret service (otherwise he could be, what I know, an editor at Liberation), who holds as true only what he acknowledges.
The top secret information about Berlusconi that the US embassy in Rome sent to the State Department was the same as Newsweek published the week before.
So why did the revelations about these files make so much noise?
On the one hand, they say what any cultivated person already knows, namely that embassies, at least since the end of the Second World War, and since the heads of state can call each other or take a plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of a few small representation exercises, have turned into spy centers.
Any viewer of investigative films knows this very well, and it is only by hypocrisy that we pretend to ignore it.
However, repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy, and serves to misplace American diplomacy.
Second, the idea that any hacker can capture the most secretive secrets of the world’s most powerful country is a significant blow to the State Department’s prestige.
Therefore, the scandal does not put the victims in crisis as much as the “stupid ones”.
But let’s come to the deep nature of what happened.
In Orwell’s time, one could conceive of all power as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
The Orwellian prophecy had been completely true since, being able to control every movement through the telephone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the highway taken and so on, the citizen became the total victim of the eye of power.
But when we demonstrate, as it happens now, that even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control report ceases to be unidirectional and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker – elected as the citizen’s avenger – can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that no longer has the ability to keep its own secrets hold?
It is true, Georg Simmel already said, that a real secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true, that everything to know about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is indeed an empty secret of secrecy, because it belongs in the public domain; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks did, that Hillary Clinton’s secrets were empty secrets means to take away all power from her.
WikiLeaks has done no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but has done too much harm to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound inflicted on a very powerful power?
It is obvious that in the future, states will no longer be able to post any confidential information online - that would be like publishing it on a poster pasted around the corner.
But it is equally obvious that with current technologies, it is hopeless to be able to maintain confidential reports over the phone.
Nothing is easier than finding out if and when a head of state flew a plane and contacted one of his colleagues.
How will private and confidential relationships be maintained in the future?
I know well that, for the moment, my prediction is science fiction and is therefore novelistic, but I am obliged to imagine government agents who move discreetly in diligences with uncontrollable routes, carrying only messages learned by heart or, at most, hiding the few information written in the heel of a chase.
The information will be kept as a single copy in locked drawers: at bottom, the Watergate spying attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that technology is now advancing in crab, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet restored a telegraph on wires (telephones).
Video cassettes (analog) had allowed film researchers to explore a film step by step, going back and forth and discovering all the secrets of editing, while now CDs (digital) only allow to jump from chapter to chapter, that is, in macroportions.
With high-speed trains, you can get from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, and the trips it includes, it takes three and a half hours.
It is not surprising, therefore, that the politics and techniques of communication return to horse cars.
One last observation.
In the past, the press was trying to understand what was being plotted in the secrecy of embassies.
Now, it is the embassies that are requesting confidential information from the press.
