Another crucial element is the distribution between donations and loans.
Again, there is no rule and everyone chooses their own method of calculation.
Some, such as France, consider that 1€ lent is equivalent to 1€ given.
Of course, this is hardly justifiable: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be justified for some investments that are profitable (often projects related to mitigation of emissions that rely on more efficient technologies), it is misleading to present a euro that will be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is given... At most, should be counted under its commitments only the cost of the loan to the lending country (i.e. a rate equivalent).
But France has nothing to do with such a reasoning: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by making 91.5% of loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% of donations (36.1 million euros) - see the EU document to check for yourself.
It is the only EU country to use the loan so massively.
Germany requires 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (otherwise) meet their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union puts 1 euro to meet its commitment, France only puts 10 cents and considers the effort comparable.
Nice tour of passe-passe!
In short, in its fast start financing, France operates a double scam: on the one hand on the evolution of the action over time and on the other hand on the reality of the financial effort.
By spending only 36.1 million euros, it manages to make believe that it spends 420 million "new and additional" in line with its promises.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that it was Bercy who carried out the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other member states continue to give if it is enough to lend?) and in the negotiations since the developing countries are not completely fooled...
The chapter on early funding is only a small, relatively short-term issue compared to all the climate discussions.
But it could be one more grain of sand in the huge machine that is the UNFCCC.
Hopefully this will not be the case.
In any case, the lessons learned from this first year of early funding are essential.
First, France could announce a change in its method of accounting for the years 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its commitments and fairness with the other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France could advance discussions on the issues of long-term financing (another crucial chapter currently discussed): we will not escape the question of "additionality" or how to account for loans.
France could change its position to become as progressive on these issues as it is on others.
The hope therefore rests on the new Minister of the Environment, Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about France's fast start and its vision of "additionality" and the use of loans would increase the level of international confidence needed to move forward in the discussions.
Alert to pesticides ingested by children
A 10-year-old child ingests 81 different chemicals in one day, according to a study published Wednesday by the association Générations Futures (formerly Movement for the Rights and Respect of Future Generations).
The association, which warns that its results "have no significant statistical value in relation to the small number of samples analyzed, but are illustrative of the problem treated", bought between July and September the foods usually consumed in four meals and a snack in one day by a child of about ten years old, in supermarkets of Oise and Paris.
These standard meals, including official recommendations - five fresh fruits and vegetables, three dairy products and 1.5 liters of water per day - as well as treats, were examined by laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The assessment of the plate is overwhelming: 81 chemicals of which 42 are classified as possible or probable carcinogens and five substances classified as certain carcinogens as well as 37 substances likely to act as endocrine disruptors (EP), according to studies by several institutions such as the International Cancer Research Centre.
"Although, in almost all cases, the legal limits for each chemical taken individually are not exceeded, it is clear from our survey that the reality of consumer exposure to potentially carcinogenic and/or PE contaminants is of concern," the association notes.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than a dozen possible carcinogenic residues and three proven as certain carcinogens as well as nearly twenty residues that can disrupt the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, predicted as a snack by the study, has traces of six chemicals, one of which is a fungicide banned in France.
The same goes for Kenyan green beans, included in lunch, on which the study detected traces of a potent insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, minced steak, canned tuna, and even breadstick and chewing gum were loaded with pesticides and other chemicals.
In the tap water the analysis revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
For dinner, the salmon steak was the "richest" with 34 chemical residues detected and even the examination of the plastic plate used to heat the meal in the microwave was not exempt from it.
The final consumer risk of this "cocktail contaminant" "is probably underestimated," according to the study.
The Alliance Europe Ecologie-Les Verts (EE-LV), for its part, proposed "faced with the urgency of the situation" to establish a moratorium on the use of pesticides, in order to stop "the increase in diseases of civilization".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EFSA) reported the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruits and vegetables consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
